{
  "doc_id": "36933",
  "text": "Tubulointerstitial damage can be a result of hypertension, development of oxidative stress, and elevation of vasoconstrictive substances, all of which are evident in the DOCA-salt animal model. It has been previously demonstrated that IMD administration induces a hypotensive response in both normotensive and hypertensive rats [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Although we found IMD to decrease blood pressure in DOCA-salt rats, accompanied by a potent diuretic action, it is possible that reduction of blood pressure alone is not solely responsible for the renal protective effects observed. Indeed, Dworkin et al. [CITATION_4] reported that blood pressure decline offered no histological protection in DOCA-salt hypertensive rats. Furthermore, a recent study showed that suppression of NF-B activity was found to be protective against renal inflammation and fibrosis with no effect on the development of hypertension [CITATION_5] . Therefore, it is highly likely that IMD has some organ protective actions independent of blood pressure reduction.",
